          <td bgcolor="#00693F" height="170"> <TABLE WIDTH=100% border="0" cellpadding="6"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD><font size="5" face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif"> I've got a brilliant idea for any new ccgs!  AND it's simple.  Decipher PLEASE READ!</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD><font size="2" face="Arial, sans-serif">Submitted by:neal</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><TABLE WIDTH=100% border="0" cellpadding="6"><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><BR>nothing new, just want to bring this to the front for decipher to read since several new card games are coming out (jedi knights/LOTR).  Please make future cards with a reversable pattern on back to avoid worrying about card orientation!  it&#146;s that simple. <BR>
<B>neal</B></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><BR>Clear vs Coloured Back
Clear plastics are a weaker plastic...the seal between the layers is thinner in width.  Coloured back plastics are tougher and more durable and make the cards stand out more.  Clear plastics aren't as wide or as thick so your deck appears smaller than the wider and thicker coloured back plastics.  Also if you put the coloured back plastics in a pile with the open end facing you.  Because of the thickness of the plastics you can see the tips of the cards... place some white border cards into your deck...you'll see that you can pick them out easy when they're stacked.   Just noticed this the other day and set out in replacing my WB with black... hard to do though for premiere anyways... but thanks to foils it's all good :)

Glyph <BR>
<B>Unknown Glyph</B></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><BR>yeah, and while we are doing that, why don't we write in BIG RED LETTERS on the back of the card what the name is...I mean hey...it would be alot easier...right? <BR>
<B>RogueGunner</B></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><BR>If you really want to cheat, you're gonna find a way. It doesn't help that some systems seem to be upside down (ls force icons on bottom of ds card) and my natural tendency is to flip them over. I play against my brother and I see him do that and I know it's a system. Anybody know the reason for that? (sites upside down) <BR>
<B>dparker</B></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><BR>Some people do cheat.  One tournement, there was one person who had some of his cards facing in opposite directions.
When I asked the td to look, all of those cards were sites......coincidence, I think not.  I do not even play with sleeves, believe it or not.
But then again I do not give a @#$% about the condition of my cards, as long as they are not marked, or heavily creased.
I do not have too cheat to win games, and if you do, well you suck...I am bored at school... so i am just ranting here.
so dont mind me....... <BR>
